            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sloane McKenzie\u2019s life is measured in the controlled chaos of a dinner rush, a cadence she prefers to the manicured quiet of her Walnut Creek upbringing. Raised by a software engineer father and a real estate agent mother, her childhood was one of comfortable predictability. While her parents envisioned a corporate path, Sloane found her sanctuary in her grandmother\u2019s kitchen, captivated by the alchemy of simple ingredients transformed into shared joy. This passion felt more tangible and alive than any spreadsheet or sales pitch.\n\nShe saw her escape in San Francisco State University, deliberately choosing a Hospitality Management degree as a declaration of intent. To fund her studies, she took a server job in North Beach, quickly learning that she thrived under pressure. The clatter of plates and the symphony of orders were her element. After graduating, she methodically climbed the industry ladder: shift supervisor at a Hayes Valley bistro, then Assistant Manager at a bustling FiDi spot. Each role honed her skills in managing inventory, staff, and the delicate egos of both chefs and customers.\n\nHer major turning point came four years ago when she was hired as the General Manager of \"Cassis,\" a popular Cal-French restaurant in the Castro. The previous owner, a neighborhood icon nearing retirement, saw in Sloane not just a manager but a kindred spirit who understood that a restaurant is a community hub. He mentored her for a year before selling to a small restaurant group, but only on the condition that Sloane remain in charge.\n\nToday, Sloane\u2019s life is inextricably linked to the Castro. Her 0.8-mile walk to work is a daily ritual, a chance to greet the owners of the local bookstore and coffee shop. Her days are a blur of scheduling, ordering wine, placating demanding patrons, and celebrating successes with her tight-knit staff, who have become her de facto family. Social life is a late-night drink with industry friends or a rare, quiet Tuesday spent reading in Dolores Park. Having recently ended a long-term relationship with someone who couldn\u2019t handle her demanding schedule, she\u2019s poured her energy back into her work. Sloane dreams of one day becoming a part-owner of Cassis or opening her own intimate wine bar in a quieter corner of the city. She didn't just find a career in San Francisco; she found a home, a community, and a purpose, one perfectly plated dish at a time."
